15///|
16/// A big integer represented as an array of Int.
17//
18// Design explained:
19// - Why use an FixedArray of Int with a len field instead of a Array[Int]?
20//   - It follows the principle of least dependency in MoonBit's core.
21//   - In our case, we always do one-off array allocation for each BigInt.
22// - Why keep a separate len field instead of using limbs.length()?
23//   - Since we always do only once array allocation for each BigInt, we
24//     often need to estimate the number of limbs needed before allocating.
25//     Using len allows us to accommodate leading zeros.
26//
27// Invariants:
28// - len > 0
29// - forall 0 <= i < len. 0 <= limbs[i] < radix
30// - (exists 0 <= i < len. limbs[i] > 0) => limbs[len-1] > 0
31// - (forall 0 <= i < len. limbs[i] == 0) => limbs[0] == 0 and len == 1
32// - forall len <= i < limbs.length(). limbs[i] == 0
33struct BigInt {
34  
FixedArray[UInt]
A big integer represented as an array of Int.

type FixedArray[A]
FixedArray[
UInt
UInt] // Note: do not use limbs.length(), use len instead because of leading zeros

Performs a bitwise left shift operation on an unsigned 64-bit integer.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The unsigned 64-bit integer to be shifted.
    • 

  • shift : The number of positions to shift the bits to the left. Must be
between 0 and 63 inclusive, values outside this range will be masked with &  63.
    • 

Returns the result of shifting self left by shift positions. For each
position shifted, the rightmost bit is filled with 0, and the leftmost bit is
discarded.
Example:
test "UInt64::op_shl" {
  let x = 1UL
  inspect!(x << 3, content="8") // 1 shifted left by 3 positions becomes 8
  inspect!(x << 63, content="9223372036854775808") // 1 shifted left by 63 positions
}
<<

    • 

  • radix_bit_len is multiple of 4
    • 

  • radix_bit_len <= 32

Performs subtraction between two unsigned 64-bit integers. When the result
would be negative, the function wraps around using modular arithmetic (2^64).
Parameters:
    

  • self : The first unsigned 64-bit integer (minuend).
    • 

  • other : The second unsigned 64-bit integer to subtract from the first
(subtrahend).
    • 

Returns the difference between the two numbers, wrapped around if necessary.
Example:
test "UInt64::op_sub" {
  let a = 5UL
  let b = 3UL
  inspect!(a - b, content="2")
  let c = 3UL
  let d = 5UL
  inspect!(c - d, content="18446744073709551614") // wraps around to 2^64 - 2
}

Converts a 32-bit signed integer to a 64-bit signed integer. All 32-bit
integers can be represented exactly in 64-bit integer format, so the
conversion is lossless.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The 32-bit signed integer to be converted.
    • 

Returns a 64-bit signed integer that represents the same numerical value as
the input.
Example:
test "Int::to_int64" {
  let n = 42
  inspect!(n.to_int64(), content="42")
  let neg = -42
  inspect!(neg.to_int64(), content="-42")
}

Converts an unsigned 32-bit integer to an unsigned 64-bit integer by
zero-extending it. The resulting value preserves the original number's
magnitude while using 64 bits to represent it.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The unsigned 32-bit integer (UInt) to be converted.
    • 

Returns an unsigned 64-bit integer (UInt64) representing the same numerical
value as the input.
Example:
test "UInt::to_uint64" {
  let n = 42U
  inspect!(n.to_uint64(), content="42")
  let max = 4294967295U // Maximum value of UInt
  inspect!(max.to_uint64(), content="4294967295")
}

(Int64) -> Int64
Performs unary negation on a 64-bit signed integer, returning its arithmetic
inverse.
Parameters:
    

  • value : The 64-bit signed integer to negate.
    • 

Returns the arithmetic negation of the input value. For all inputs except
Int64::min_value(), returns the value with opposite sign. When the input is
Int64::min_value(), returns Int64::min_value() due to two's complement
representation.
Example:
test "Int64::op_neg" {
  inspect!(-42L, content="-42")
  inspect!(--42L, content="42")
  inspect!(-9223372036854775808L, content="-9223372036854775808") // negating min value
}

Reinterprets a 64-bit signed integer as an unsigned 64-bit integer without
changing its bit pattern. The reinterpretation follows the standard two's
complement representation rules.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The 64-bit signed integer to be reinterpreted.
    • 

Returns a 64-bit unsigned integer that has the same bit pattern as the input.
Example:
test "Int64::reinterpret_as_uint64" {
  let neg = -1L
  inspect!(neg.reinterpret_as_uint64(), content="18446744073709551615") // All bits set to 1
  let pos = 42L
  inspect!(pos.reinterpret_as_uint64(), content="42") // Positive numbers remain unchanged
}

    •

FixedArray[UInt]
A big integer represented as an array of Int.
limbs: 
(Int, UInt) -> FixedArray[UInt]
Creates a new fixed-size array with the specified length, initializing all
elements with the given value.
Parameters:
    

  • length : The length of the array to create. Must be non-negative.
    • 

  • initial_value : The value used to initialize all elements in the array.
    • 

Returns a new fixed-size array of type FixedArray[T] with length
elements, where each element is initialized to initial_value.
Throws a panic if length is negative.
Example:
test "FixedArray::make" {
  let arr = FixedArray::make(3, 42)
  inspect!(arr[0], content="42")
  inspect!(arr.length(), content="3")
}

test "panic FixedArray::make/negative_length" {
  ignore(FixedArray::make(-1, 0))
}

FixedArray[UInt]
limbs
(FixedArray[UInt], Int, UInt) -> Unit
Sets a value at the specified index in a fixed-size array. The original value
at that index is overwritten.
Parameters:
    

  • array : The fixed-size array to modify.
    • 

  • index : The position in the array where the value will be set.
    • 

  • value : The new value to assign at the specified index.
    • 

Throws a runtime error if the index is out of bounds (less than 0 or greater
than or equal to the length of the array).
Example:
test "FixedArray::op_set" {
  let arr = [1, 2, 3]
  arr[1] = 42
  inspect!(arr, content="[1, 42, 3]")
}

test "panic FixedArray::op_set/out_of_bounds" {
  let arr = [1, 2, 3]
  arr[3] = 42 // Index out of bounds
}
@alert unsafe "Panic if index is out of bounds."

Calculates the remainder of dividing one unsigned 64-bit integer by another.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The dividend unsigned 64-bit integer.
    • 

  • other : The divisor unsigned 64-bit integer.
    • 

Returns the remainder of the division operation.
Throws a panic if the divisor is zero.
Example:
test "UInt64::op_mod" {
  let a = 17UL
  let b = 5UL
  inspect!(a % b, content="2") // 17 divided by 5 gives quotient 3 and remainder 2
  inspect!(7UL % 4UL, content="3")
}

test "panic UInt64::op_mod/division_by_zero" {
  let a = 42UL
  ignore(a % 0UL) // Panics: division by zero
}

218///|
219/// Adds two arbitrary-precision integers. Handles positive and negative numbers
220/// correctly by converting subtraction of negative numbers into addition of
221/// positive numbers.
222///
223/// Parameters:
224///
225/// * `self` : The first big integer to add.
226/// * `other` : The second big integer to add.
227///

229///
230/// Example:
231///

235///   let b = 1N
236///   inspect!(a + b, content="9223372036854775808") // Beyond Int64 range
237///   inspect!(-a + -b, content="-9223372036854775808")
238/// }
239/// ```

FixedArray[UInt]
limbs = 
(Int, UInt) -> FixedArray[UInt]
Creates a new fixed-size array with the specified length, initializing all
elements with the given value.
Parameters:
    

  • length : The length of the array to create. Must be non-negative.
    • 

  • initial_value : The value used to initialize all elements in the array.
    • 

Returns a new fixed-size array of type FixedArray[T] with length
elements, where each element is initialized to initial_value.
Throws a panic if length is negative.
Example:
test "FixedArray::make" {
  let arr = FixedArray::make(3, 42)
  inspect!(arr[0], content="42")
  inspect!(arr.length(), content="3")
}

test "panic FixedArray::make/negative_length" {
  ignore(FixedArray::make(-1, 0))
}

limbs
(FixedArray[UInt], Int) -> UInt
Retrieves an element at the specified index from a fixed-size array. This
function implements the array indexing operator [].
Parameters:
    

  • array : The fixed-size array to access.
    • 

  • index : The position in the array from which to retrieve the element.
    • 

Returns the element at the specified index.
Throws a runtime error if the index is out of bounds (negative or greater
than or equal to the length of the array).
Example:
test "FixedArray::op_get" {
  let arr = FixedArray::make(3, 42)
  inspect!(arr[1], content="42")
}

test "panic FixedArray::op_get/out_of_bounds" {
  let arr = FixedArray::make(3, 0)
  ignore(arr[3]) // Index out of bounds
}

Adds two 64-bit unsigned integers. This is the implementation of the +
operator for UInt64.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The first unsigned 64-bit integer operand.
    • 

  • other : The second unsigned 64-bit integer operand.
    •

  let a = 42UL
  let b = 100UL
  inspect!(a + b, content="142")

  // Demonstrate overflow behavior

  inspect!(max + 1UL, content="0")
}

266///|
267/// Subtracts one arbitrary-precision integer from another. Handles positive and
268/// negative numbers appropriately.
269///
270/// Parameters:
271///
272/// * `self` : The minuend (the number to subtract from).
273/// * `other` : The subtrahend (the number to be subtracted).
274///

276/// `other`.
277///
278/// Example:
279///
280/// ```moonbit
281/// test "BigInt::op_sub" {
282///   let a = 12345678901234567890N
283///   let b = 9876543210987654321N
284///   inspect!(a - b, content="2469135690246913569")
285///   inspect!(-a - b, content="-22222222112222222211")
286/// }
287/// ```

operation is useful for low-level bit manipulation and type conversions where

according to two's complement arithmetic.

  • self : The first 64-bit integer operand.

(Int64) -> UInt64
Reinterprets a 64-bit signed integer as an unsigned 64-bit integer without
changing its bit pattern. The reinterpretation follows the standard two's
complement representation rules.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The 64-bit signed integer to be reinterpreted.
    •

Example:
test "Int64::reinterpret_as_uint64" {
  let neg = -1L
  inspect!(neg.reinterpret_as_uint64(), content="18446744073709551615") // All bits set to 1
  let pos = 42L
  inspect!(pos.reinterpret_as_uint64(), content="42") // Positive numbers remain unchanged
}

338///|
339/// Multiplies two arbitrary-precision integers. Uses the most efficient
340/// multiplication algorithm based on the size of the operands:
341///
342/// * Grade school multiplication for small numbers
343/// * Karatsuba multiplication for large numbers
344///
345/// Parameters:
346///
347/// * `self` : The first arbitrary-precision integer to multiply.
348/// * `other` : The second arbitrary-precision integer to multiply.
349///
350/// Returns the product of the two numbers. The sign of the result follows the
351/// standard multiplication rules: positive if both operands have the same sign,
352/// negative otherwise.
353///
354/// Example:
355///
356/// ```moonbit
357/// test "BigInt::op_mul" {
358///   let a = 12345678901234567890N
359///   let b = -98765432109876543210N
360///   inspect!(a * b, content="-1219326311370217952237463801111263526900")
361///   inspect!(a * 0N, content="0")
362/// }
363/// ```
364pub impl 
trait Mul {
  op_mul(Self, Self) -> Self
}
types implementing this trait can use the * operator

Creates a new fixed-size array with the specified length, initializing all
elements with the given value.
Parameters:
    

  • length : The length of the array to create. Must be non-negative.
    • 

  • initial_value : The value used to initialize all elements in the array.

Converts an unsigned 32-bit integer to an unsigned 64-bit integer by
zero-extending it. The resulting value preserves the original number's
magnitude while using 64 bits to represent it.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The unsigned 32-bit integer (UInt) to be converted.
    •

value as the input.
Example:
test "UInt::to_uint64" {
  let n = 42U
  inspect!(n.to_uint64(), content="42")
  let max = 4294967295U // Maximum value of UInt
  inspect!(max.to_uint64(), content="4294967295")
}
to_uint64() 
(UInt64, UInt64) -> UInt64
Adds two 64-bit unsigned integers. This is the implementation of the +
operator for UInt64.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The first unsigned 64-bit integer operand.
    • 

  • other : The second unsigned 64-bit integer operand.
    • 

Returns the sum of the two unsigned 64-bit integers. If the result overflows,
it wraps around modulo 2^64.
Example:
test "UInt64::op_add" {
  let a = 42UL
  let b = 100UL
  inspect!(a + b, content="142")

  // Demonstrate overflow behavior
  let max = 18446744073709551615UL
  inspect!(max + 1UL, content="0")
}

(UInt64, UInt64) -> UInt64
Performs multiplication between two unsigned 64-bit integers.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The first unsigned 64-bit integer operand.
    • 

  • other : The second unsigned 64-bit integer operand.
    • 

Returns the product of the two unsigned 64-bit integers. The result wraps

  let a = 2UL
  let b = 3UL
  inspect!(a * b, content="6")

  // Demonstrate wrapping behavior
  let max = 18446744073709551615UL
  inspect!(max * 2UL, content="18446744073709551614") // Wraps around to max - 1
}

  arr[3] = 42 // Index out of bounds

type FixedArray[A]

half, 0U)
421  
FixedArray[UInt]
lower.
(FixedArray[UInt], Int, FixedArray[UInt], Int, Int) -> Unit
Copies a slice of elements from one fixed array to another.
This function copies len elements from src starting at src_offset to dst starting at dst_offset.
The arrays may overlap, in which case the copy is performed in a way that preserves the data.
Example
let src = FixedArray::from_array([1, 2, 3, 4, 5])
let dst = FixedArray::from_array([0, 0, 0, 0, 0])
FixedArray::unsafe_blit(dst, 0, src, 0, 3)
assert_eq!(dst, FixedArray::from_array([1, 2, 3, 0, 0]))
The behavior is undefined and platform-specific if:
    

  • len < 0
    • 

  • src_offset < 0
    • 

  • dst_offset < 0
    • 

  • dst_offset + len > dst.length()

Creates a new fixed-size array with the specified length, initializing all
elements with the given value.
Parameters:
    

  • length : The length of the array to create. Must be non-negative.
    •

FixedArray[UInt]
upper.
(FixedArray[UInt], Int, FixedArray[UInt], Int, Int) -> Unit
Copies a slice of elements from one fixed array to another.
This function copies len elements from src starting at src_offset to dst starting at dst_offset.
The arrays may overlap, in which case the copy is performed in a way that preserves the data.
Example
let src = FixedArray::from_array([1, 2, 3, 4, 5])
let dst = FixedArray::from_array([0, 0, 0, 0, 0])
FixedArray::unsafe_blit(dst, 0, src, 0, 3)
assert_eq!(dst, FixedArray::from_array([1, 2, 3, 0, 0]))
The behavior is undefined and platform-specific if:
    

  • len < 0
    • 

  • src_offset < 0
    • 

  • dst_offset < 0
    • 

  • dst_offset + len > dst.length()
    • 

  • src_offset + len > src.length()
    •

431/// Performs division between two arbitrary-precision integers, following
432/// standard arithmetic rules for signed division.
433///
434/// Parameters:
435///
436/// * `self` : The dividend big integer.
437/// * `other` : The divisor big integer.
438///
439/// Returns the quotient of the division.
440///
441/// Throws a panic if the divisor is zero.
442///
443/// Example:
444///
445/// ```moonbit
446/// test "BigInt::op_div" {
447///   let a = BigInt::from_string("100")
448///   let b = BigInt::from_string("20")
449///   inspect!(a / b, content="5")
450///   inspect!(-a / b, content="-5")
451///   inspect!(a / -b, content="-5")
452///   inspect!(-a / -b, content="5")
453/// }
454///
455/// test "panic BigInt::op_div/division_by_zero" {
456///   let a = BigInt::from_string("100")
457///   let b = BigInt::from_string("0")
458///   ignore(a / b) // Division by zero
459/// }
460/// ```

zero-extending it. The resulting value preserves the original number's

(UInt64, Int) -> UInt64
Performs a bitwise left shift operation on an unsigned 64-bit integer.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The unsigned 64-bit integer to be shifted.
    • 

  • shift : The number of positions to shift the bits to the left. Must be
between 0 and 63 inclusive, values outside this range will be masked with &  63.
    • 

Returns the result of shifting self left by shift positions. For each
position shifted, the rightmost bit is filled with 0, and the leftmost bit is
discarded.
Example:
test "UInt64::op_shl" {
  let x = 1UL
  inspect!(x << 3, content="8") // 1 shifted left by 3 positions becomes 8
  inspect!(x << 63, content="9223372036854775808") // 1 shifted left by 63 positions
}

    • 

  • radix_bit_len <= 32

(UInt64, UInt64) -> UInt64
Adds two 64-bit unsigned integers. This is the implementation of the +
operator for UInt64.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The first unsigned 64-bit integer operand.
    • 

  • other : The second unsigned 64-bit integer operand.
    • 

Returns the sum of the two unsigned 64-bit integers. If the result overflows,
it wraps around modulo 2^64.
Example:
test "UInt64::op_add" {
  let a = 42UL
  let b = 100UL
  inspect!(a + b, content="142")

  // Demonstrate overflow behavior
  let max = 18446744073709551615UL
  inspect!(max + 1UL, content="0")
}

Retrieves an element at the specified index from a fixed-size array. This
function implements the array indexing operator [].
Parameters:
    

  • array : The fixed-size array to access.
    • 

  • index : The position in the array from which to retrieve the element.

  inspect!(arr.length(), content="3")

Converts an unsigned 32-bit integer to an unsigned 64-bit integer by

to_uint64().
(UInt64) -> Int64
Reinterprets the bits of an unsigned 64-bit integer as a signed 64-bit
integer. The bits remain the same, but their interpretation changes. This
operation is useful for low-level bit manipulation and type conversions where
you want to preserve the exact bit pattern.
Parameters:
    

  • value : The unsigned 64-bit integer (UInt64) to be reinterpreted.
    • 

Returns a signed 64-bit integer (Int64) that has the same bit pattern as
the input value.
Example:
test "UInt64::reinterpret_as_int64" {
  let max = 18446744073709551615UL // Maximum value of UInt64
  inspect!(max.reinterpret_as_int64(), content="-1") // All bits set to 1 represents -1 in two's complement
}
reinterpret_as_int64().
(Int64) -> Int
Counts the number of leading zero bits in a 64-bit signed integer, starting
from the most significant bit.
Parameters:
    

  • number : The 64-bit signed integer whose leading zeros are to be counted.
    • 

Returns the number of leading zero bits (0 to 64).
Example:
test "Int64::clz" {
  let a = 0x0000_0001_0000_0000L
  inspect!(a.clz(), content="31") // 31 leading zeros before the first 1 bit
  let b = 0L
  inspect!(b.clz(), content="64") // All bits are zero
}

Sets a value at the specified index in a fixed-size array. The original value
at that index is overwritten.
Parameters:
    

  • array : The fixed-size array to modify.
    • 

  • index : The position in the array where the value will be set.
    • 

  • value : The new value to assign at the specified index.
    • 

Throws a runtime error if the index is out of bounds (less than 0 or greater
than or equal to the length of the array).
Example:
test "FixedArray::op_set" {
  let arr = [1, 2, 3]
  arr[1] = 42
  inspect!(arr, content="[1, 42, 3]")
}

test "panic FixedArray::op_set/out_of_bounds" {
  let arr = [1, 2, 3]
  arr[3] = 42 // Index out of bounds
}

u0 
(UInt64, UInt64) -> UInt64
Performs multiplication between two unsigned 64-bit integers.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The first unsigned 64-bit integer operand.
    • 

  • other : The second unsigned 64-bit integer operand.
    • 

Returns the product of the two unsigned 64-bit integers. The result wraps
around if it exceeds the maximum value of UInt64.
Example:
test "UInt64::op_mul" {
  let a = 2UL
  let b = 3UL
  inspect!(a * b, content="6")

  // Demonstrate wrapping behavior
  let max = 18446744073709551615UL
  inspect!(max * 2UL, content="18446744073709551614") // Wraps around to max - 1
}
* 
UInt64
The base of the number system.
radix 
(UInt64, UInt64) -> UInt64
Adds two 64-bit unsigned integers. This is the implementation of the +
operator for UInt64.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The first unsigned 64-bit integer operand.
    • 

  • other : The second unsigned 64-bit integer operand.
    • 

Returns the sum of the two unsigned 64-bit integers. If the result overflows,
it wraps around modulo 2^64.
Example:
test "UInt64::op_add" {
  let a = 42UL
  let b = 100UL
  inspect!(a + b, content="142")

  // Demonstrate overflow behavior
  let max = 18446744073709551615UL
  inspect!(max + 1UL, content="0")
}

(UInt64, UInt64) -> UInt64
Performs division operation between two unsigned 64-bit integers.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The dividend unsigned 64-bit integer.
    • 

  • other : The divisor unsigned 64-bit integer.
    • 

Returns the quotient of dividing the dividend by the divisor.
Throws a runtime error if other is zero.

test "UInt64::op_div" {
  let a = 100UL
  let b = 20UL
  inspect!(a / b, content="5") // Using infix operator
}

test "panic UInt64::op_div/division_by_zero" {
  let a = 42UL
  ignore(a / 0UL) // Throws runtime error: division by zero

  let a = 2UL
  let b = 3UL
  inspect!(a * b, content="6")

  // Demonstrate wrapping behavior
  let max = 18446744073709551615UL
  inspect!(max * 2UL, content="18446744073709551614") // Wraps around to max - 1
}

radix 
(UInt64, UInt64) -> UInt64
Adds two 64-bit unsigned integers. This is the implementation of the +
operator for UInt64.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The first unsigned 64-bit integer operand.
    • 

  • other : The second unsigned 64-bit integer operand.
    • 

Returns the sum of the two unsigned 64-bit integers. If the result overflows,
it wraps around modulo 2^64.
Example:
test "UInt64::op_add" {
  let a = 42UL
  let b = 100UL
  inspect!(a + b, content="142")

  // Demonstrate overflow behavior
  let max = 18446744073709551615UL
  inspect!(max + 1UL, content="0")
}
+ 
UInt64
u1 
(UInt64, UInt64) -> UInt64
Performs subtraction between two unsigned 64-bit integers. When the result
would be negative, the function wraps around using modular arithmetic (2^64).
Parameters:
    

  • self : The first unsigned 64-bit integer (minuend).
    • 

  • other : The second unsigned 64-bit integer to subtract from the first
(subtrahend).
    • 

Returns the difference between the two numbers, wrapped around if necessary.
Example:
test "UInt64::op_sub" {
  let a = 5UL
  let b = 3UL
  inspect!(a - b, content="2")
  let c = 3UL
  let d = 5UL
  inspect!(c - d, content="18446744073709551614") // wraps around to 2^64 - 2
}

(FixedArray[UInt64], Int) -> UInt64
Retrieves an element at the specified index from a fixed-size array. This
function implements the array indexing operator [].
Parameters:
    

  • array : The fixed-size array to access.
    • 

  • index : The position in the array from which to retrieve the element.
    • 

Returns the element at the specified index.
Throws a runtime error if the index is out of bounds (negative or greater
than or equal to the length of the array).
Example:
test "FixedArray::op_get" {
  let arr = FixedArray::make(3, 42)
  inspect!(arr[1], content="42")
}

test "panic FixedArray::op_get/out_of_bounds" {
  let arr = FixedArray::make(3, 0)
  ignore(arr[3]) // Index out of bounds
}

(Int64, Int64) -> Int64
Adds two 64-bit integers together. Performs overflow checking and wrapping
according to two's complement arithmetic.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The first 64-bit integer operand.
    • 

  • other : The second 64-bit integer operand to add to the first.
    •

(UInt64) -> Int64
Reinterprets the bits of an unsigned 64-bit integer as a signed 64-bit
integer. The bits remain the same, but their interpretation changes. This
operation is useful for low-level bit manipulation and type conversions where
you want to preserve the exact bit pattern.
Parameters:
    

  • value : The unsigned 64-bit integer (UInt64) to be reinterpreted.
    • 

Returns a signed 64-bit integer (Int64) that has the same bit pattern as
the input value.
Example:
test "UInt64::reinterpret_as_int64" {
  let max = 18446744073709551615UL // Maximum value of UInt64
  inspect!(max.reinterpret_as_int64(), content="-1") // All bits set to 1 represents -1 in two's complement
}

(FixedArray[UInt64], Int, UInt64) -> Unit
Sets a value at the specified index in a fixed-size array. The original value
at that index is overwritten.
Parameters:
    

  • array : The fixed-size array to modify.
    • 

  • index : The position in the array where the value will be set.
    • 

  • value : The new value to assign at the specified index.
    • 

Throws a runtime error if the index is out of bounds (less than 0 or greater
than or equal to the length of the array).
Example:
test "FixedArray::op_set" {
  let arr = [1, 2, 3]
  arr[1] = 42
  inspect!(arr, content="[1, 42, 3]")
}

  let arr = [1, 2, 3]
  arr[3] = 42 // Index out of bounds
}

(Int64) -> UInt64
Reinterprets a 64-bit signed integer as an unsigned 64-bit integer without
changing its bit pattern. The reinterpretation follows the standard two's
complement representation rules.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The 64-bit signed integer to be reinterpreted.
    •

test "Int64::reinterpret_as_uint64" {
  let neg = -1L
  inspect!(neg.reinterpret_as_uint64(), content="18446744073709551615") // All bits set to 1
  let pos = 42L
  inspect!(pos.reinterpret_as_uint64(), content="42") // Positive numbers remain unchanged
}

borrow 
(Int64, Int) -> Int64
Performs arithmetic right shift operation on a 64-bit integer value by a
specified number of bits. Preserves the sign bit of the original number while
shifting its bits right, filling the leftmost positions with copies of the
sign bit.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The 64-bit integer value to be shifted.
    • 

  • shift_count : The number of positions to shift right. Must be
non-negative and less than 64.
    • 

Returns a new Int64 value that represents the result of shifting self
right by shift_count bits.
Example:
test "Int64::op_shr" {
  let n = -1024L
  inspect!(n >> 3, content="-128") // Preserves sign bit
  let p = 1024L
  inspect!(p >> 3, content="128") // Regular right shift for positive numbers
}

    • 

  • radix can only be a power of 2
    • 

  • radix_bit_len is multiple of 4
    • 

  • radix_bit_len <= 32

UInt64
carry = 
UInt64
carry 
(UInt64, Int) -> UInt64
Performs a logical right shift operation on a 64-bit unsigned integer by a
specified number of bits. All bits shifted beyond the least significant bit
are discarded, and zeros are shifted in from the most significant bit.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The 64-bit unsigned integer to be shifted.
    • 

  • shift : The number of positions to shift right. Only the least
significant 6 bits of this value are used, effectively making the shift count
always between 0 and 63.
    • 

Returns a new UInt64 value representing the result of the right shift
operation.
Example:
test "UInt64::op_shr" {
  let x = 0xFF00FF00FF00FF00UL
  inspect!(x >> 8, content="71777214294589695") // Shifted right by 8 bits
  inspect!(x >> 64, content="18374966859414961920") // Equivalent to x >> 0 due to masking
}

    •

  let max = 18446744073709551615UL
  inspect!(max + 1UL, content="0")

(UInt64, Int) -> UInt64
Performs a logical right shift operation on a 64-bit unsigned integer by a
specified number of bits. All bits shifted beyond the least significant bit
are discarded, and zeros are shifted in from the most significant bit.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The 64-bit unsigned integer to be shifted.
    • 

  • shift : The number of positions to shift right. Only the least
significant 6 bits of this value are used, effectively making the shift count
always between 0 and 63.
    • 

Returns a new UInt64 value representing the result of the right shift
operation.
Example:
test "UInt64::op_shr" {
  let x = 0xFF00FF00FF00FF00UL
  inspect!(x >> 8, content="71777214294589695") // Shifted right by 8 bits
  inspect!(x >> 64, content="18374966859414961920") // Equivalent to x >> 0 due to masking
}
>>

    • 

  • radix can only be a power of 2
    • 

  • radix_bit_len is multiple of 4
    • 

  • radix_bit_len <= 32

according to two's complement arithmetic.
Parameters:

    •

(UInt64) -> Int64
Reinterprets the bits of an unsigned 64-bit integer as a signed 64-bit
integer. The bits remain the same, but their interpretation changes. This
operation is useful for low-level bit manipulation and type conversions where
you want to preserve the exact bit pattern.
Parameters:
    

  • value : The unsigned 64-bit integer (UInt64) to be reinterpreted.
    • 

Returns a signed 64-bit integer (Int64) that has the same bit pattern as
the input value.
Example:
test "UInt64::reinterpret_as_int64" {
  let max = 18446744073709551615UL // Maximum value of UInt64
  inspect!(max.reinterpret_as_int64(), content="-1") // All bits set to 1 represents -1 in two's complement
}

qh 
(UInt64, UInt64) -> UInt64
Performs subtraction between two unsigned 64-bit integers. When the result
would be negative, the function wraps around using modular arithmetic (2^64).
Parameters:
    

  • self : The first unsigned 64-bit integer (minuend).
    • 

  • other : The second unsigned 64-bit integer to subtract from the first
(subtrahend).
    • 

Returns the difference between the two numbers, wrapped around if necessary.
Example:
test "UInt64::op_sub" {
  let a = 5UL
  let b = 3UL
  inspect!(a - b, content="2")
  let c = 3UL
  let d = 5UL
  inspect!(c - d, content="18446744073709551614") // wraps around to 2^64 - 2
}

671///|
672/// Performs a left shift operation on a `BigInt` value. Preserves the sign of
673/// the original number while shifting only its absolute value.
674///
675/// Parameters:
676///
677/// * `self` : The `BigInt` value to be shifted.
678/// * `n` : The number of positions to shift left. Must be non-negative.
679///
680/// Returns a new `BigInt` value that is the result of shifting the absolute
681/// value of the input left by `n` positions, maintaining the original sign.
682///
683/// Throws a panic if the shift count is negative.
684///
685/// Example:
686///
687/// ```moonbit
688/// test "BigInt::op_shl" {
689///   let x = 5N
690///   inspect!(x << 2, content="20")
691///   let y = -5N
692///   inspect!(y << 2, content="-20")
693/// }
694///
695/// test "panic BigInt::op_shl/negative_shift" {
696///   let x = 5N
697///   ignore(x << -1) // Panics with "negative shift count"
698/// }
699/// ```
700pub impl 
trait Shl {
  op_shl(Self, Int) -> Self
}
types implementing this trait can use the << operator

  len: Int

Performs a bitwise OR operation between two unsigned 64-bit integers.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The first unsigned 64-bit integer operand.
    • 

  • other : The second unsigned 64-bit integer operand.
    • 

Returns a new UInt64 value with bits set to 1 where either or both operands
have bits set to 1, and 0 where both operands have bits set to 0.
Example:
test "UInt64::lor" {
  let a = 0xF0F0F0F0UL
  let b = 0x0F0F0F0FUL
  inspect!(a | b, content="4294967295") // All bits set to 1
}

Retrieves an element at the specified index from a fixed-size array. This
function implements the array indexing operator [].
Parameters:
    

  • array : The fixed-size array to access.
    • 

  • index : The position in the array from which to retrieve the element.
    • 

Returns the element at the specified index.
Throws a runtime error if the index is out of bounds (negative or greater
than or equal to the length of the array).
Example:
test "FixedArray::op_get" {
  let arr = FixedArray::make(3, 42)
  inspect!(arr[1], content="42")
}

test "panic FixedArray::op_get/out_of_bounds" {
  let arr = FixedArray::make(3, 0)
  ignore(arr[3]) // Index out of bounds
}

(UInt) -> UInt64
Converts an unsigned 32-bit integer to an unsigned 64-bit integer by
zero-extending it. The resulting value preserves the original number's
magnitude while using 64 bits to represent it.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The unsigned 32-bit integer (UInt) to be converted.
    • 

Returns an unsigned 64-bit integer (UInt64) representing the same numerical
value as the input.
Example:
test "UInt::to_uint64" {
  let n = 42U
  inspect!(n.to_uint64(), content="42")
  let max = 4294967295U // Maximum value of UInt
  inspect!(max.to_uint64(), content="4294967295")
}
to_uint64() 
(UInt64, Int) -> UInt64
Performs a bitwise left shift operation on an unsigned 64-bit integer.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The unsigned 64-bit integer to be shifted.
    • 

  • shift : The number of positions to shift the bits to the left. Must be
between 0 and 63 inclusive, values outside this range will be masked with &  63.
    • 

Returns the result of shifting self left by shift positions. For each
position shifted, the rightmost bit is filled with 0, and the leftmost bit is
discarded.
Example:
test "UInt64::op_shl" {
  let x = 1UL
  inspect!(x << 3, content="8") // 1 shifted left by 3 positions becomes 8
  inspect!(x << 63, content="9223372036854775808") // 1 shifted left by 63 positions
}

Parameters:
    

  • array : The fixed-size array to modify.
    • 

  • index : The position in the array where the value will be set.
    • 

  • value : The new value to assign at the specified index.
    • 

Throws a runtime error if the index is out of bounds (less than 0 or greater
than or equal to the length of the array).
Example:
test "FixedArray::op_set" {
  let arr = [1, 2, 3]
  arr[1] = 42
  inspect!(arr, content="[1, 42, 3]")

  arr[3] = 42 // Index out of bounds

Performs a logical right shift operation on a 64-bit unsigned integer by a
specified number of bits. All bits shifted beyond the least significant bit
are discarded, and zeros are shifted in from the most significant bit.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The 64-bit unsigned integer to be shifted.
    • 

  • shift : The number of positions to shift right. Only the least
significant 6 bits of this value are used, effectively making the shift count
always between 0 and 63.
    • 

Returns a new UInt64 value representing the result of the right shift
operation.
Example:
test "UInt64::op_shr" {
  let x = 0xFF00FF00FF00FF00UL
  inspect!(x >> 8, content="71777214294589695") // Shifted right by 8 bits
  inspect!(x >> 64, content="18374966859414961920") // Equivalent to x >> 0 due to masking
}

FixedArray[UInt]
new_limbs.
(FixedArray[UInt], Int, FixedArray[UInt], Int, Int) -> Unit
Copies a slice of elements from one fixed array to another.
This function copies len elements from src starting at src_offset to dst starting at dst_offset.
The arrays may overlap, in which case the copy is performed in a way that preserves the data.
Example
let src = FixedArray::from_array([1, 2, 3, 4, 5])
let dst = FixedArray::from_array([0, 0, 0, 0, 0])
FixedArray::unsafe_blit(dst, 0, src, 0, 3)
assert_eq!(dst, FixedArray::from_array([1, 2, 3, 0, 0]))
The behavior is undefined and platform-specific if:
    

  • len < 0
    • 

  • src_offset < 0
    • 

  • dst_offset < 0
    • 

  • dst_offset + len > dst.length()
    • 

  • src_offset + len > src.length()
    • 

unsafe_blit(

733///|
734/// Performs arithmetic right shift operation on a big integer value. The shift
735/// operation preserves the sign of the number while shifting the absolute value
736/// right by `n` bits. For negative numbers, the result is rounded towards
737/// negative infinity.
738///
739/// Parameters:
740///
741/// * `self` : The big integer value to be shifted.
742/// * `n` : The number of bits to shift right. Must be non-negative.
743///
744/// Returns a new `BigInt` value that represents the result of shifting `self`
745/// right by `n` bits.
746///
747/// Throws a panic if `n` is negative.
748///
749/// Example:
750///
751/// ```moonbit
752/// test "BigInt::op_shr" {
753///   let n = BigInt::from_string("1024")
754///   inspect!(n >> 3, content="128")
755///   let neg = BigInt::from_string("-1024")
756///   inspect!(neg >> 3, content="-128")
757/// }
758///
759/// test "panic BigInt::op_shr/negative_shift" {
760///   let n = BigInt::from_string("1024")
761///   ignore(n >> -1) // Panics with "negative shift count"
762/// }
763/// ```
764pub impl 
trait Shr {
  op_shr(Self, Int) -> Self
}
types implementing this trait can use the >> operator

(UInt64, Int) -> UInt64
Performs a bitwise left shift operation on an unsigned 64-bit integer.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The unsigned 64-bit integer to be shifted.
    • 

  • shift : The number of positions to shift the bits to the left. Must be
between 0 and 63 inclusive, values outside this range will be masked with &  63.
    • 

Returns the result of shifting self left by shift positions. For each
position shifted, the rightmost bit is filled with 0, and the leftmost bit is
discarded.

  inspect!(x << 63, content="9223372036854775808") // 1 shifted left by 63 positions

826///|
827/// Compares two arbitrary-precision integers and returns their relative order.
828///
829/// Parameters:
830///
831/// * `self` : The first arbitrary-precision integer to compare.
832/// * `other` : The second arbitrary-precision integer to compare.
833///
834/// Returns an integer indicating the relative order:
835///
836/// * A negative value if `self` is less than `other`
837/// * Zero if `self` equals `other`
838/// * A positive value if `self` is greater than `other`
839///
840/// Example:
841///
842/// ```moonbit
843/// test "BigInt::compare" {
844///   let a = BigInt::from_string("42")
845///   let b = BigInt::from_string("24")
846///   let c = BigInt::from_string("-42")
847///   inspect!(a.compare(b), content="1") // 42 > 24
848///   inspect!(b.compare(a), content="-1") // 24 < 42
849///   inspect!(c.compare(a), content="-1") // -42 < 42
850///   inspect!(a.compare(a), content="0") // 42 = 42
851/// }
852/// ```

  • positive, if the first argument is greater

conversion preserves the exact value since all integers in the range of Int
can be represented exactly as Double values.

Retrieves an element at the specified index from a fixed-size array. This
function implements the array indexing operator [].
Parameters:
    

  • array : The fixed-size array to access.
    • 

  • index : The position in the array from which to retrieve the element.

than or equal to the length of the array).

(UInt) -> UInt64
Converts an unsigned 32-bit integer to an unsigned 64-bit integer by
zero-extending it. The resulting value preserves the original number's
magnitude while using 64 bits to represent it.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The unsigned 32-bit integer (UInt) to be converted.
    • 

Returns an unsigned 64-bit integer (UInt64) representing the same numerical
value as the input.
Example:
test "UInt::to_uint64" {
  let n = 42U
  inspect!(n.to_uint64(), content="42")
  let max = 4294967295U // Maximum value of UInt
  inspect!(max.to_uint64(), content="4294967295")
}
to_uint64().
(UInt64) -> Int64
Reinterprets the bits of an unsigned 64-bit integer as a signed 64-bit
integer. The bits remain the same, but their interpretation changes. This
operation is useful for low-level bit manipulation and type conversions where
you want to preserve the exact bit pattern.
Parameters:
    

  • value : The unsigned 64-bit integer (UInt64) to be reinterpreted.
    • 

Returns a signed 64-bit integer (Int64) that has the same bit pattern as
the input value.
Example:
test "UInt64::reinterpret_as_int64" {
  let max = 18446744073709551615UL // Maximum value of UInt64
  inspect!(max.reinterpret_as_int64(), content="-1") // All bits set to 1 represents -1 in two's complement
}

(Int64, Int) -> Int64
Performs a left shift operation on a 64-bit integer value. Shifts the bits of
the first operand to the left by the number of positions specified by the
second operand. The rightmost positions are filled with zeros.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The 64-bit integer value to be shifted.
    • 

  • shift : The number of positions to shift the bits to the left. Must be
non-negative and less than 64.
    • 

Returns a new Int64 value representing the result of the left shift
operation.
Example:
test "Int64::op_shl" {
  let n = 1L
  inspect!(n << 3, content="8") // 1 shifted left by 3 positions becomes 8
  let m = -4L
  inspect!(m << 2, content="-16") // -4 shifted left by 2 positions becomes -16
}

(Int64, Int64) -> Int64
Performs a bitwise OR operation between two 64-bit integers.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The first 64-bit integer operand.
    • 

  • other : The second 64-bit integer operand.
    •

1009/// Converts a decimal string representation to a BigInt value. The string can
1010/// optionally start with a minus sign (-) to indicate a negative number,

Adds two 64-bit unsigned integers. This is the implementation of the +
operator for UInt64.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The first unsigned 64-bit integer operand.
    • 

  • other : The second unsigned 64-bit integer operand.

1079/// Converts a hexadecimal string to a `BigInt`. The string can be prefixed with
1080/// a minus sign (`-`) to indicate a negative number. The string must contain
1081/// only hexadecimal digits (`0-9`, `a-f`, or `A-F`).
1082///
1083/// Parameters:
1084///
1085/// * `input` : A string containing the hexadecimal representation of an integer.
1086/// Must be non-empty and contain only valid hexadecimal digits. May be prefixed
1087/// with a minus sign to indicate a negative number.
1088///
1089/// Returns a `BigInt` value representing the hexadecimal number.
1090///
1091/// Throws a runtime error if:
1092///
1093/// * The input string is empty.
1094/// * The input string contains characters other than hexadecimal digits (0-9,
1095/// a-f, A-F) or a leading minus sign.
1096///
1097/// Example:
1098///
1099/// ```moonbit
1100/// test "BigInt::from_hex" {
1101///   inspect!(BigInt::from_hex("ff"), content="255")
1102///   inspect!(BigInt::from_hex("-ff"), content="-255")
1103///   inspect!(BigInt::from_hex("DEADBEEF"), content="3735928559")
1104/// }
1105///
1106/// test "panic BigInt::from_hex/invalid_input" {
1107///   ignore(BigInt::from_hex("")) // Empty string
1108///   ignore(BigInt::from_hex("0x123")) // Invalid prefix
1109///   ignore(BigInt::from_hex("12g")) // Invalid character
1110/// }
1111/// ```
1112pub fn 
struct BigInt {
  limbs: FixedArray[UInt]
  sign: Sign
  len: Int
}

Performs a bitwise OR operation between two unsigned 32-bit integers. For
each bit position, the result is 1 if at least one of the corresponding bits
in either operand is 1.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The first unsigned 32-bit integer operand.

  • other : The second unsigned 32-bit integer operand.
    •

  let a = 0xF0F0U // Binary: 1111_0000_1111_0000
  let b = 0x0F0FU // Binary: 0000_1111_0000_1111
  inspect!(a | b, content="65535") // Binary: 1111_1111_1111_1111
}

Performs a bitwise OR operation between two unsigned 32-bit integers. For
each bit position, the result is 1 if at least one of the corresponding bits
in either operand is 1.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The first unsigned 32-bit integer operand.
    • 

  • other : The second unsigned 32-bit integer operand.
    • 

Returns the result of the bitwise OR operation as an unsigned 32-bit integer.
Example:
test "UInt::lor" {
  let a = 0xF0F0U // Binary: 1111_0000_1111_0000
  let b = 0x0F0FU // Binary: 0000_1111_0000_1111
  inspect!(a | b, content="65535") // Binary: 1111_1111_1111_1111
}

1177///   inspect!(neg.to_hex(), content="-FF")

FixedArray[UInt]
new_limbs.
(FixedArray[UInt], Int, FixedArray[UInt], Int, Int) -> Unit
Copies a slice of elements from one fixed array to another.
This function copies len elements from src starting at src_offset to dst starting at dst_offset.
The arrays may overlap, in which case the copy is performed in a way that preserves the data.
Example
let src = FixedArray::from_array([1, 2, 3, 4, 5])
let dst = FixedArray::from_array([0, 0, 0, 0, 0])
FixedArray::unsafe_blit(dst, 0, src, 0, 3)
assert_eq!(dst, FixedArray::from_array([1, 2, 3, 0, 0]))
The behavior is undefined and platform-specific if:
    

  • len < 0
    • 

  • src_offset < 0
    • 

  • dst_offset < 0
    • 

  • dst_offset + len > dst.length()
    • 

  • src_offset + len > src.length()
    •

1242///|
1243/// Computes the result of raising a `BigInt` to the power of another `BigInt`,
1244/// with an optional modulus.
1245///
1246/// When a modulus is provided, computes the modular exponentiation using the
1247/// square-and-multiply algorithm. This is particularly useful in cryptographic
1248/// applications where direct exponentiation would result in numbers too large to
1249/// handle efficiently.
1250///
1251/// Parameters:
1252///
1253/// * `self` : The base number to be raised to a power.
1254/// * `exp` : The exponent (must be non-negative).
1255/// * `modulus` : Optional modulus for modular exponentiation (must be positive
1256/// if provided).
1257///
1258/// Returns the result of the exponentiation, or the result modulo `modulus` if a
1259/// modulus is provided.
1260///
1261/// Throws:
1262///
1263/// * Aborts if the exponent is negative.
1264/// * Aborts if the provided modulus is zero or negative.
1265///
1266/// Example:
1267///
1268/// ```moonbit
1269/// test "BigInt::pow" {
1270///   let base = BigInt::from_string("3")
1271///   let exp = BigInt::from_string("4")
1272///   inspect!(base.pow(exp), content="81")
1273///   inspect!(base.pow(exp, modulus=BigInt::from_string("10")), content="1")
1274/// }
1275///
1276/// test "panic BigInt::pow/negative_exponent" {
1277///   let base = BigInt::from_string("3")
1278///   let exp = BigInt::from_string("-1")
1279///   ignore(base.pow(exp))
1280/// }
1281/// ```
1282pub fn 
struct BigInt {
  limbs: FixedArray[UInt]
  sign: Sign
  len: Int
}

1318/// Converts a big-endian byte sequence to a `BigInt` value with an optional
1319/// sign. Interprets the input bytes as a big-endian representation of an
1320/// unsigned integer, and applies the specified sign to create the final `BigInt`
1321/// value.
1322///
1323/// Parameters:
1324///
1325/// * `bytes` : A sequence of bytes representing the magnitude of the number in
1326/// big-endian order. The sequence must not be empty unless `sign` is 0.
1327/// * `sign` : An integer specifying the sign of the resulting number (default:
1328/// 1). A value of 1 creates a positive number, -1 creates a negative number, and
1329/// 0 returns zero regardless of the input bytes.
1330///
1331/// Returns a `BigInt` value representing the number encoded in the byte sequence
1332/// with the specified sign.
1333///
1334/// Throws a panic if the input byte sequence is empty and the sign is not 0.
1335///
1336/// Example:
1337///
1338/// ```moonbit
1339/// test "BigInt::from_octets" {
1340///   let bytes = b"\x01\x02\x03" // Represents 0x010203
1341///   let positive = BigInt::from_octets(bytes)
1342///   let negative = BigInt::from_octets(bytes, signum=-1)
1343///   inspect!(positive, content="66051")
1344///   inspect!(negative, content="-66051")
1345/// }
1346///
1347/// test "panic BigInt::from_octets/empty" {
1348///   ignore(BigInt::from_octets(b"")) // Panics with "empty octet string"
1349/// }
1350/// ```

Sets a value at the specified index in a fixed-size array. The original value

Parameters:
    

  • array : The fixed-size array to modify.
    •

1386///|
1387/// Converts a non-negative arbitrary-precision integer to a big-endian byte
1388/// sequence. The output can be padded with leading zeros to meet a specified
1389/// length requirement, but only if the actual length is less than the requested
1390/// length.
1391///
1392/// Parameters:
1393///
1394/// * `self` : The arbitrary-precision integer to convert. Must be non-negative.
1395/// * `length` : Optional minimum length of the output byte sequence. If
1396/// provided, must be positive. Defaults to 1 if not specified.
1397///
1398/// Returns a byte sequence representing the number in big-endian order, possibly
1399/// padded with leading zeros to reach the specified length.
1400///
1401/// Throws a panic if:
1402///
1403/// * The input number is negative
1404/// * The specified length is negative or zero
1405///
1406/// Example:
1407///
1408/// ```moonbit
1409/// test "BigInt::to_octets" {
1410///   let n = BigInt::from_hex("abcdef")
1411///   inspect!(n.to_octets(length=4), content="b\"\\x00\\xab\\xcd\\xef\"")
1412///   let m = BigInt::from_string("0")
1413///   inspect!(m.to_octets(), content="b\"\\x00\"")
1414/// }
1415///
1416/// test "panic BigInt::to_octets/negative" {
1417///   let n = -BigInt::from_hex("abcdef")
1418///   ignore(n.to_octets()) // Panics with "negative BigInt"
1419///   let m = BigInt::from_hex("abcdef")
1420///   ignore(m.to_octets(length=-1)) // Panics with "negative length"
1421/// }
1422/// ```
1423pub fn

  sign: Sign
  len: Int
}

each bit position, the result is 1 if the bits at that position in both
operands are 1, and 0 otherwise.

  let b = 0xFF00U // 1111_1111_0000_0000
  inspect!(a & b, content="61440") // 1111_0000_0000_0000 = 61440

(Int) -> Byte
Converts a 32-bit signed integer to a byte by taking its least significant 8
bits. Any bits beyond the first 8 bits are truncated.
Parameters:
    

  • value : The 32-bit signed integer to be converted. Only the least

  inspect!(n.to_byte(), content="b'\\x02'") // Only keeps 00000010

  inspect!(neg.to_byte(), content="b'\\xFF'") // Only keeps 11111111

1447///|
1448/// Performs a bitwise AND operation between two arbitrary-precision integers.
1449///
1450/// The operation is performed using two's complement representation, which means
1451/// it handles both positive and negative numbers correctly. For negative
1452/// numbers, the function first converts them to their two's complement form,
1453/// performs the AND operation, and then converts the result back if necessary.
1454///
1455/// Parameters:
1456///
1457/// * `self` : The first arbitrary-precision integer operand.
1458/// * `other` : The second arbitrary-precision integer operand.
1459///
1460/// Returns a new `BigInt` representing the result of the bitwise AND operation.
1461///
1462/// Example:
1463///
1464/// ```moonbit
1465/// test "BigInt::land" {
1466///   let a = BigInt::from_string("42") // 0b101010
1467///   let b = BigInt::from_string("-12") // ~0b1011 + 1
1468///   inspect!(a & b, content="32") // 0b100000
1469/// }
1470///
1471/// test "BigInt::land/negative" {
1472///   let a = BigInt::from_string("-8") // ~0b111 + 1
1473///   let b = BigInt::from_string("-4") // ~0b11 + 1
1474///   inspect!(a & b, content="-8") // ~0b1011 + 1
1475/// }
1476/// ```
1477pub impl 
trait BitAnd {
  land(Self, Self) -> Self
}
types implementing this trait can use the & operator

Creates a new fixed-size array with the specified length, initializing all
elements with the given value.
Parameters:

    •

FixedArray
type FixedArray[A]
::make(
Int
max_length, 0U)..
(FixedArray[UInt], Int, FixedArray[UInt], Int, Int) -> Unit
Copies a slice of elements from one fixed array to another.
This function copies len elements from src starting at src_offset to dst starting at dst_offset.
The arrays may overlap, in which case the copy is performed in a way that preserves the data.
Example
let src = FixedArray::from_array([1, 2, 3, 4, 5])
let dst = FixedArray::from_array([0, 0, 0, 0, 0])
FixedArray::unsafe_blit(dst, 0, src, 0, 3)
assert_eq!(dst, FixedArray::from_array([1, 2, 3, 0, 0]))
The behavior is undefined and platform-specific if:
    

  • len < 0
    • 

  • src_offset < 0
    • 

  • dst_offset < 0
    • 

  • dst_offset + len > dst.length()
    • 

  • src_offset + len > src.length()
    • 

unsafe_blit(

(FixedArray[UInt], Int, FixedArray[UInt], Int, Int) -> Unit
Copies a slice of elements from one fixed array to another.
This function copies len elements from src starting at src_offset to dst starting at dst_offset.
The arrays may overlap, in which case the copy is performed in a way that preserves the data.
Example
let src = FixedArray::from_array([1, 2, 3, 4, 5])
let dst = FixedArray::from_array([0, 0, 0, 0, 0])
FixedArray::unsafe_blit(dst, 0, src, 0, 3)
assert_eq!(dst, FixedArray::from_array([1, 2, 3, 0, 0]))
The behavior is undefined and platform-specific if:
    

  • len < 0
    • 

  • src_offset < 0
    • 

  • dst_offset < 0
    • 

  • dst_offset + len > dst.length()
    • 

  • src_offset + len > src.length()
    •

1564/// Performs a bitwise OR operation between two arbitrary-precision integers,
1565/// following two's complement representation for negative numbers.

1567/// Parameters:

1569/// * `self` : The first arbitrary-precision integer operand.

1573///

1575///
1576/// ```moonbit
1577/// test "BigInt::lor" {
1578///   let a = BigInt::from_string("42")

(FixedArray[UInt], Int, FixedArray[UInt], Int, Int) -> Unit
Copies a slice of elements from one fixed array to another.
This function copies len elements from src starting at src_offset to dst starting at dst_offset.
The arrays may overlap, in which case the copy is performed in a way that preserves the data.
Example
let src = FixedArray::from_array([1, 2, 3, 4, 5])
let dst = FixedArray::from_array([0, 0, 0, 0, 0])
FixedArray::unsafe_blit(dst, 0, src, 0, 3)
assert_eq!(dst, FixedArray::from_array([1, 2, 3, 0, 0]))
The behavior is undefined and platform-specific if:
    

  • len < 0
    • 

  • src_offset < 0
    • 

  • dst_offset < 0
    • 

  • dst_offset + len > dst.length()
    • 

  • src_offset + len > src.length()
    •

FixedArray[UInt]
A big integer represented as an array of Int.
limbs: 
(Int, UInt) -> FixedArray[UInt]
Creates a new fixed-size array with the specified length, initializing all
elements with the given value.
Parameters:
    

  • length : The length of the array to create. Must be non-negative.
    • 

  • initial_value : The value used to initialize all elements in the array.
    • 

Returns a new fixed-size array of type FixedArray[T] with length
elements, where each element is initialized to initial_value.
Throws a panic if length is negative.
Example:
test "FixedArray::make" {
  let arr = FixedArray::make(3, 42)
  inspect!(arr[0], content="42")
  inspect!(arr.length(), content="3")
}

test "panic FixedArray::make/negative_length" {
  ignore(FixedArray::make(-1, 0))
}
FixedArray
type FixedArray[A]
::make(
Int
max_length 
(Int, Int) -> Int
- 1, 0U)..
(FixedArray[UInt], Int, FixedArray[UInt], Int, Int) -> Unit
Copies a slice of elements from one fixed array to another.
This function copies len elements from src starting at src_offset to dst starting at dst_offset.
The arrays may overlap, in which case the copy is performed in a way that preserves the data.
Example
let src = FixedArray::from_array([1, 2, 3, 4, 5])
let dst = FixedArray::from_array([0, 0, 0, 0, 0])
FixedArray::unsafe_blit(dst, 0, src, 0, 3)
assert_eq!(dst, FixedArray::from_array([1, 2, 3, 0, 0]))
The behavior is undefined and platform-specific if:
    

  • len < 0
    • 

  • src_offset < 0
    • 

  • dst_offset < 0
    • 

  • dst_offset + len > dst.length()
    • 

  • src_offset + len > src.length()
    • 

unsafe_blit(

1785/// Converts a `BigInt` to a 32-bit signed integer (`Int`).
1786///
1787/// Parameters:
1788///
1789/// * `self` : The `BigInt` value to be converted.
1790///
1791/// Returns a 32-bit signed integer representing the lower 32 bits of the input
1792/// `BigInt`.
1793///
1794/// Example:
1795///
1796/// ```moonbit
1797/// test "BigInt::to_int" {
1798///   let big = 2147483648N // 2^31
1799///   inspect!(big.to_int(), content="-2147483648") // Overflow to Int.min_value
1800/// }
1801/// ```

  sign: Sign
  len: Int
}

to_uint64().
(UInt64) -> Int64
Reinterprets the bits of an unsigned 64-bit integer as a signed 64-bit
integer. The bits remain the same, but their interpretation changes. This
operation is useful for low-level bit manipulation and type conversions where
you want to preserve the exact bit pattern.
Parameters:
    

  • value : The unsigned 64-bit integer (UInt64) to be reinterpreted.
    • 

Returns a signed 64-bit integer (Int64) that has the same bit pattern as
the input value.
Example:
test "UInt64::reinterpret_as_int64" {
  let max = 18446744073709551615UL // Maximum value of UInt64
  inspect!(max.reinterpret_as_int64(), content="-1") // All bits set to 1 represents -1 in two's complement
}
reinterpret_as_int64()

result 
(UInt64, Int) -> UInt64
Performs a bitwise left shift operation on an unsigned 64-bit integer.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The unsigned 64-bit integer to be shifted.
    • 

  • shift : The number of positions to shift the bits to the left. Must be
between 0 and 63 inclusive, values outside this range will be masked with &  63.
    • 

Returns the result of shifting self left by shift positions. For each
position shifted, the rightmost bit is filled with 0, and the leftmost bit is
discarded.
Example:
test "UInt64::op_shl" {
  let x = 1UL
  inspect!(x << 3, content="8") // 1 shifted left by 3 positions becomes 8
  inspect!(x << 63, content="9223372036854775808") // 1 shifted left by 63 positions
}

  • radix_bit_len <= 32

(UInt64, UInt64) -> UInt64
Performs a bitwise OR operation between two unsigned 64-bit integers.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The first unsigned 64-bit integer operand.
    • 

  • other : The second unsigned 64-bit integer operand.
    • 

Returns a new UInt64 value with bits set to 1 where either or both operands
have bits set to 1, and 0 where both operands have bits set to 0.
Example:
test "UInt64::lor" {
  let a = 0xF0F0F0F0UL
  let b = 0x0F0F0F0FUL
  inspect!(a | b, content="4294967295") // All bits set to 1
}

FixedArray[UInt]
A big integer represented as an array of Int.
limbs
(FixedArray[UInt], Int) -> UInt
Retrieves an element at the specified index from a fixed-size array. This
function implements the array indexing operator [].
Parameters:
    

  • array : The fixed-size array to access.
    • 

  • index : The position in the array from which to retrieve the element.
    • 

Returns the element at the specified index.
Throws a runtime error if the index is out of bounds (negative or greater
than or equal to the length of the array).
Example:
test "FixedArray::op_get" {
  let arr = FixedArray::make(3, 42)
  inspect!(arr[1], content="42")
}

test "panic FixedArray::op_get/out_of_bounds" {
  let arr = FixedArray::make(3, 0)
  ignore(arr[3]) // Index out of bounds
}
[i].
(UInt) -> UInt64
Converts an unsigned 32-bit integer to an unsigned 64-bit integer by
zero-extending it. The resulting value preserves the original number's
magnitude while using 64 bits to represent it.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The unsigned 32-bit integer (UInt) to be converted.
    • 

Returns an unsigned 64-bit integer (UInt64) representing the same numerical
value as the input.
Example:
test "UInt::to_uint64" {
  let n = 42U
  inspect!(n.to_uint64(), content="42")
  let max = 4294967295U // Maximum value of UInt
  inspect!(max.to_uint64(), content="4294967295")
}

Performs a bitwise AND operation between two unsigned 64-bit integers.
Parameters:
    

  • self : The first unsigned 64-bit integer operand.
    • 

  • other : The second unsigned 64-bit integer operand.
    • 

Returns the result of performing a bitwise AND operation on the two operands.
Example:
test "UInt64::land" {
  let a = 0xF0F0F0F0F0F0F0F0UL
  let b = 0xFF00FF00FF00FF00UL
  inspect!(a & b, content="17294086455919964160") // 0xF000F000F000F000
}
